Renay's husband as a youngster enjoyed the night life. He was typically one to go home in the wee hours. Living in deep rural Jamaica, there were no street lights at the time, so the journey home was usually dark. One night on his way home he was attacked by a wolf like pack of dogs. The dogs were very strategic in their attack. Some stayed in front to push him towards those in the rear, who nipped at his Achilles heel. He mustered up enough strength to kick and jump over those that were attacking from the front. He then ran and sought rescue in a nearby shop. But he had to get home...so like the dogs he too had to devise a strategy. He gathered up as many stones as he could possibly carry and took his journey. After hurling and wounding a few of his attackers he was able to make it home safely. On subsequent late night trips he would arm himself with stones and knock them together upon approaching his enemys' camp. The dogs being wounded by the stones before would only bark at him from a distance. 
Isn't it just like the enemy? To lay wait for your soul in the dark? To encircle you and attack from behind? If you know your enemy, arm yourself with the word of God and sound them as you approach their camp, they will stay far!

The "Cool Walk" and "Cool Skip" is one one of the 6 ESSENTIAL dribbles needed for effective guard play. "Ball turning," not carrying, is one of the 14 #Ball #Control Principles needed to develop into a #monster handler! The Cool Walk/Skip is THE most important dribble concept that can be taught.

The "Cool Walk/Skip" allows for you to:

1. Control Pace and defender (won't be sped up) without body contact unless #neccessary
2. Handle Pressure/Protect the Ball
3. Transition seamlessly into protection breakdowns or faceup atttacks
4. Patiently wait for plays
*5. Conserve energy
6. Flow 
7. Offset defensive quickness and size in most instances

I promised follow up on the Charles procedure and here it is! If you didn't see the previous posts on this case, go back and check them out!
.
.
The Charles procedure was a procedure described for recalcitrant lymphedema. It is rarely done anymore because there are much better treatments for lymphedema and it's almost a procedure of historical interest... but still has its role in limb salvage. .
.
The procedure itself is simple- debulk all dead skin and subcutaneous tissue to the level of fascia. No muscle is taken. The limb is allowed to granulate for a bit and then split thickness sling grafted circumferentially. .
.
This limb was salvaged rather than amputated at the patient's wishes. She had not neurologic or vascular injury. This will give her a reliable leg to walk on- she has an open hip dislocation treated with a girdlestone and 3b open pilon on the other side... so this side is actually her better leg!
.
.
.
